[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Multi-System Orchestration With Tool-Using LLMs and Verified Action Closure
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Digital Tools For Twenty Years
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical workflow, has been a phone-and-fax-centric problem for decades. The reason is structural. Care coordination requires asking, repeatedly, "what is this patient supposed to be doing right now, who is responsible for the next action, has the next action actually happened, and if not, what is in the way." The questions are specific to the care journey. The questions for a post-MI patient are different from the questions for a post-cancer-diagnosis multi-specialist patient. The questions in the first 30 days post-discharge are different from the questions in the second 30 days. The questions when an appointment was successfully scheduled are different from the questions when an authorization is pending. The recommendations are also journey-specific, are calibrated to the patient's specific situation, and depend on the actual status of multiple distinct systems and entities at the moment of the conversation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing care coordinators do, when they do this well, is hold a multi-entity coordinating model in their heads, supplemented by chart notes, scheduling systems, and a collection of phone numbers and faxes. The model includes "what episode are we coordinating," "what is the protocol for this episode," "what milestones have been met," "what milestones are pending," "what blockers exist for the pending milestones," "who is the right person at each entity to call about each blocker," and "what does the patient need to do, what can I do for them, and what needs the human team's involvement." Holding this model is most of the cognitive work; the actual phone calls and the actual conversations are easier once the model is in place.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first generation of digital care-coordination tools, roughly the 2010s, tried to systematize this with patient portals and to-do lists. The portals showed the patient the appointments that had been scheduled and the medications that had been prescribed; the to-do lists reminded the patient about pending follow-ups. The clinical evidence was modest. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for portal-based and reminder-based care-coordination interventions includes various studies with mixed effects on clinical outcomes; specific findings vary by intervention design and population --> The fundamental problem these tools had was that they treated the patient as the integrating agent. The patient is the entity least equipped for the integration work, and the tools that delegated the integration to the patient ended up helping the patients who were already most able to do their own coordination, while leaving the patients who needed the most help largely unserved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second generation, roughly 2018 to 2024, layered analytics, risk stratification, and automated outreach on top. Predictive models identified high-risk patients; automated messages prompted them about specific follow-up needs; care management workflows pulled high-risk cases into queues for human follow-up. The clinical evidence was more promising for the high-risk subset that received human follow-up; for the broad middle, automated reminders without action capability remained limited. The fundamental constraint was that automation without integration depth produced reminders without resolution, and the work of resolving the small problems that came up during coordination remained almost entirely human.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What changed, around 2024, is that tool-using LLMs got good enough to function as the integrating agent. A care coordination assistant, deployed with careful institutional governance, can hold the multi-entity coordinating model the human coordinator holds (it has the discharge summary, the medication list, the referrals, the appointment status across systems, the authorization status, and the patient's recent communications with the coordination assistant), can engage in the kinds of warm, specific conversations the human coordinator would have, can take a meaningful subset of the coordinating actions directly through system integrations, and can escalate to the human team for cases requiring judgment. The LLM is not a coordinator. The LLM is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the coordination workflow operate at population scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "remind-and-display" to "orchestrate-verify-and-resolve." The assistant's value is concentrated in three places: the multi-system orchestration (taking actions across multiple systems on the patient's behalf), the action closure verification (confirming that actions actually happened, that artifacts were actually exchanged, that authorizations were actually granted), and the operational reach (extending care-coordination coverage from a small subset of high-risk patients to the broad coordination-needing majority).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active care episodes, episode-specific protocols, current open items, recent system-status snapshots, conversation history with the assistant), access to a structured library of episode-specific protocols, and a careful set of tools for reading and writing across multiple systems. The LLM conducts conversations and orchestrates tool calls. The protocols encode the journey-specific logic. The tools handle the deterministic actions and the system-of-record interactions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one conversation. It is a stream of conversational episodes within a longer-running care-coordination episode (which itself may be days, weeks, or months long), sometimes initiated by the patient, sometimes initiated by the assistant when a milestone or status change warrants engagement, sometimes triggered by an event in an integrated system (an appointment was scheduled, an authorization was approved, a referral was completed, a lab result came back, a medication was filled, an appointment was missed).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The assistant's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode initialization.** A care coordination episode begins when the patient enters a coordination-eligible state: discharge from a hospital, diagnosis of a condition that requires multi-specialist workup, enrollment in a transition-of-care program, scheduling of a complex pre-procedural workup, identification by a population-health workflow as needing coordination support. The episode is instantiated from a journey-specific protocol template, populated with patient-specific values (the discharge summary, the active medication list, the referrals ordered, the appointments already scheduled, the authorizations already submitted), signed off by the appropriate clinical team, and registered with the assistant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Milestone tracking and proactive engagement.** The protocol specifies the milestones for the episode (post-discharge primary care visit within 7-10 days, post-discharge cardiology visit within 14 days, cardiac rehab enrollment within 4 weeks, echocardiogram completion, medication-reconciliation confirmation, lab follow-up at week 4). The assistant tracks each milestone's status (not yet due, due, scheduled, completed, missed, blocked), engages the patient proactively when a milestone is approaching or when status changes, and escalates when a milestone is at risk.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Action orchestration.** The assistant takes actions on the patient's behalf, with the patient's explicit or implicit consent depending on the action class. Some actions are taken directly (scheduling an appointment via an integrated scheduling API, requesting a refill via the refill bot's API, faxing a referral to an external provider, submitting an authorization request, querying the status of an external referral). Some actions are taken by guiding the patient (you need to call this number; here is what to say; here is what to do if they say X). Some actions require human-coordinator involvement (the authorization was denied; we need to file an appeal).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Verification and closure.** For every coordination action, the assistant verifies completion. An appointment scheduled is not the same as an appointment kept. A refill submitted is not the same as a refill picked up. A referral sent is not the same as a referral seen. The assistant pulls status from integrated systems where possible, asks the patient where system status is not authoritative, and chases down cases where the action did not close.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-initiated questions and concerns.** The patient can engage at any time during the episode with questions, concerns, or status checks. The assistant answers within scope, escalates outside scope, and updates the coordination model based on what the patient discloses.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Handoff between entities.** When the coordination requires multiple entities to communicate (the hospital sending a discharge summary to primary care, the cardiology practice sending notes to primary care, the imaging center sending the echo report to cardiology, the pharmacy reconciling medications with the discharging hospital), the assistant verifies that the handoff occurred and intervenes when it did not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team escalation.** When the coordination encounters a problem the assistant cannot resolve (an authorization denial requiring an appeal, a referral that is not getting through, a scheduling problem requiring negotiation, a clinical change requiring care-plan revision, a patient disclosure requiring clinical attention), the assistant escalates to the appropriate human resource per the institution's policy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode closure.** When the episode is complete (the post-discharge protocol has been fully executed; the multi-specialist workup has produced a treatment decision; the transition has been successfully managed), the assistant transitions the patient out of episode-based coordination and into whatever follow-up posture the institution has (chronic disease coaching, periodic check-ins, no further engagement). The episode summary is delivered to the care team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run Care Coordination
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, paste in some institutional information about care coordination, and have it help patients. This breaks in several specific ways.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no view of system state.** Without integrations into the EHR, the scheduling system, the pharmacy system, the referral management system, the eligibility and authorization system, and external entities (where interoperability permits), the LLM cannot say what the patient's actual situation is. A coordination assistant without system integration is just a chatbot with general advice; it cannot tell the patient whether their appointment is on Tuesday at 10:00 AM or whether it has been canceled and rescheduled.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model cannot take actions.** Without the tool surface, the LLM can produce instructions but cannot schedule appointments, submit refills, or send referrals. Coordination assistants that produce instructions but cannot take actions inherit the limitation of the previous reminder-based generation: they help the patients who were already capable of self-coordination and miss the rest.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no episode model.** Coordination is episode-based. Without an explicit episode model that tracks where the patient is in a multi-week or multi-month protocol, the LLM treats every conversation as a fresh start, which destroys the continuity coordination requires.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model cannot verify closure.** Coordination is fundamentally about closure: did the action actually happen, did the artifact actually arrive, did the authorization actually succeed. Without verification logic that pulls system status and chases down gaps, the LLM produces a stream of suggestions without confirmation, which is exactly the problem the previous generation of tools had.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of cross-entity handoffs.** A discharge summary going from hospital to primary care office is a specific handoff with a specific verification pattern. The LLM does not know that, by default. The handoff verification logic is encoded in the protocol, not left to the LLM's interpretation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no clinical-decision-rule arithmetic.** The decision rules used in care coordination (post-discharge follow-up windows by clinical condition, authorization approval criteria, referral urgency tiers) are arithmetic on structured inputs. The LLM does this poorly. The deterministic clinical and operational rule tools encapsulate the computation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of escalation.** When an authorization is denied, when a referral is rejected, when a patient discloses they have stopped a medication, when a clinical change suggests the protocol needs revision, the response is not "I'm sorry to hear that." The response is to escalate, with the situation context attached. The escalation logic is encoded explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of staying within scope.** The patient may ask the assistant for medical advice, for triage, for diagnosis. The assistant routes those out (to the chronic disease coach, to the triage bot, to the care team, as appropriate) and stays within the coordination scope. Skipping scope discipline produces an assistant that occasionally hallucinates clinical recommendations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications.** Coordination conversations contain dense PHI (the entire care plan, the full medication list, all referrals, all authorizations, the patient's social context). The audit, retention, and access-control story has to handle this.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of multi-system identity reconciliation.** A patient at the hospital may be patient_id_A; the same patient at the primary care office may be patient_id_B; the same patient at the pharmacy is identified by a different identifier; the same patient at the insurance company is the member_id. The reconciliation across these identifiers is a deterministic operational task with high consequences for getting it wrong.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of inter-organizational interoperability variability.** Some external entities support FHIR APIs. Some support HL7 interfaces. Some support Direct Trust messaging. Some support fax. Some require phone calls. The protocol-driven multi-channel inter-organizational integration is encoded explicitly, not improvised by the LLM.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Coordination Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal context (recipe 11.7), continuous emergency screening (recipes 11.6, 11.7, 11.8). The care coordination assistant adds eight structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode-as-architectural-primitive.** A care-coordination episode is a long-running, protocol-driven, multi-milestone state machine that the assistant operates within. Without the episode model, every conversation is generic; with it, every conversation is contextualized to where the patient is in the protocol.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-system orchestration with action closure verification.** The assistant takes actions across multiple internal and external systems and verifies that each action closed. The verification is deterministic and tracked; the assistant does not consider an action complete until evidence of completion is recorded.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-entity handoff verification.** The protocol specifies the handoffs that are supposed to occur between entities (hospital to primary care, cardiology to imaging, pharmacy to discharging team). The assistant tracks each handoff's status and intervenes when it did not occur.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Identity reconciliation across systems.** The patient has different identifiers in different systems. The reconciliation is part of the integration architecture, audited, and validated against ground-truth (the institution's enterprise master patient index where one exists, or the patient's stated information cross-checked against multiple systems where it does not).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Inter-organizational interoperability hierarchy.** The protocol specifies the preferred channel for each inter-organizational interaction (FHIR API where supported, HL7 v2 where required, Direct Trust messaging for clinical document exchange, fax where the receiving entity does not support electronic options, phone where the receiving entity is voice-only). The integration layer routes appropriately.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Operational status tracking with stale-data awareness.** The assistant pulls status from integrated systems and stamps each piece of data with its retrieval time. When data is stale, the assistant either re-fetches or warns the patient (and the care team) that the status is from a snapshot rather than live.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Policy-driven action authorization.** Some actions can be taken directly by the assistant; some require explicit patient consent at the point of action; some require human-coordinator review; some require care-team clinical authorization. The action-class policy is institutional, not LLM-determined.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode-summary delivery to care team and to next-step downstream products.** When the coordination episode closes, the structured summary is delivered to the care team for review and to whatever downstream products the patient is transitioning into (chronic disease coach for ongoing management, mental health support for behavioral-health follow-up, periodic-check-in workflow for stable patients).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the previous patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Closure is the only metric that matters.** A coordination assistant that produces beautifully-worded suggestions but does not close the loop on whether the suggestions led to action is a coordination assistant that has reproduced the previous generation's failure mode. The architectural design and the operational ownership both need to keep the focus on closure, not on conversation volume.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-entity integration depth is the rate-limiting factor.** The institution's ability to integrate with external entities (other hospitals' EHRs via interop, primary care offices in the community, imaging centers, durable medical equipment vendors, home health agencies, pharmacy chains) directly determines how much of the coordination work the assistant can take on. Institutions with strong HIE connectivity, strong Direct Trust adoption, and strong relationships with downstream providers can build a much more capable assistant than institutions without.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode boundaries are clinically meaningful but operationally fuzzy.** When does the post-MI coordination episode end? When the cardiac rehab is complete? When the patient has stable lipid management? When the cardiology follow-up cadence has shifted from monthly to annually? The clinical answer varies by patient and condition; the operational answer has to be specified per protocol with named clinical-leadership ownership of the boundaries.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Authorization complexity is one of the dominant operational realities.** A meaningful fraction of the patient-facing coordination problems are authorization-related: this referral needs authorization, this medication needs authorization, this imaging study needs authorization. Each authorization has its own rules, its own timeline, its own appeal pathway, and its own risk of delay. The integration with the institution's prior authorization workflow (recipe 1.4 covers the document side; recipe 2.4 covers the letter side) is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient stress affects coordination engagement.** Patients in active coordination episodes are often patients in active medical situations. Cognitive load is elevated. Emotional reserves are limited. The assistant has to be calibrated for stressed conversation: shorter messages, more confirmation, gentler pacing, more explicit options, more graceful handling of patient frustration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Family caregivers are often the operational coordinator.** For elderly patients, pediatric patients, patients with cognitive impairment, and many post-acute patients, the family caregiver is doing most of the coordination work. The assistant's design includes support for proxy-coordination relationships with appropriate consent and access controls.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants context is part of the coordination reality.** A patient without transportation cannot get to the cardiac rehab program. A patient without pharmacy access cannot pick up the new prescription. A patient without home support cannot follow the home-health-aide schedule. The coordination assistant, when integrated with social-determinants tooling and care-navigation workflows, can identify these blockers and route to the appropriate help.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Inter-organizational miscommunication is endemic.** Discharge summaries arrive late or not at all. Referral details arrive incomplete. Authorization decisions are not communicated to the patient or to the ordering provider. The coordination assistant operates in an environment where communication failures are the rule, not the exception. The verification logic is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The assistant has to handle the operational gap between the institution and the patient's other care.** Patients see providers outside the institution. The coordination assistant has visibility into what happens inside the institution; what happens outside is visible only when the external entity reports back. Designing the assistant to handle both the visible-internal and the partially-visible-external care is one of the architectural challenges.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-episode patients need multi-episode coordination.** A patient post-MI may also be in a chronic-disease coaching relationship, may also be in a behavioral-health pathway, may also be undergoing a cancer-screening workup. The coordination assistant either runs a single integrated coordination relationship across all episodes or runs episode-specific coordination streams. The integrated pattern is more clinically valuable but architecturally harder.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode-completion is sometimes ambiguous.** A coordination episode may close on schedule, may extend due to delays, may transition to a different episode (the workup uncovered a new condition), may close incompletely (the patient never engaged with the rehab program). The episode-state-machine has to handle each case.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team integration is a specific architectural and operational discipline.** Same as the chronic disease coach: the care team has to trust the assistant, has to know when to expect alerts, has to have efficient tooling for reviewing the assistant's interactions, and has to have a feedback path for protocol revision.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is multi-quarter post-launch work.** The assistant's effect on readmission rate, on follow-up adherence, on time-to-completion of recommended workups, and on care-team capacity expansion all show up over months to years. Institutions building this with quarterly-impact expectations are typically disappointed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Interoperability has improved meaningfully in the last several years.** The 21st Century Cures Act and ONC certification rules have driven broader adoption of FHIR-based interoperability across U.S. healthcare. <!-- TODO: verify; specific compliance and adoption figures vary; the directional finding that FHIR interoperability has expanded substantially since the Cures Act is well-established --> Coordination assistants today have meaningfully better access to external entity data than coordination tools five years ago, particularly for problem-list, medication-list, and recent-encounter data through FHIR APIs and through HIE participation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-coordination-specific specialty platforms have matured.** Vendor platforms specifically focused on transitions-of-care, specialty-network coordination, and complex-care management exist and are deployed at major institutions. Most institutions building coordination assistants take a hybrid approach: build the conversational layer in-house, partner with vendor platforms for specific integrations, and use HIE participation for cross-institution data flow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle multi-system coordination well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from previous chapter 11 recipes maps cleanly to coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve episode state, retrieve system-of-record data, take coordination actions, verify closure, surface escalation flags, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid human-plus-AI coordination is the dominant production pattern.** Same as the chronic disease coach: AI assistant for routine coordination, human coordinator for complex cases. The economics work because the AI handles the routine integration work while the human focuses where their judgment is most needed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is mixed but trending positive.** Studies of structured care-coordination programs (Project RED, Project BOOST, IMPACT, and others) have demonstrated meaningful reductions in readmission rates, ED utilization, and care-coordination failures. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for structured transitions-of-care interventions includes published studies of Project RED, Project BOOST, and similar interventions; specific outcome figures vary by study --> The evidence for AI-augmented coordination specifically is earlier-stage but trending positive for hybrid AI-plus-human models.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for specific journey types.** Several vendors operate transitions-of-care programs and care-coordination platforms at major-institution scale. Most institutions run a hybrid: build a thin coordination-orchestration layer in-house on the institution's preferred infrastructure, partner with vendors for specific journey content and (sometimes) for the human-coordinator workforce, and integrate with the institution's care-management, telehealth, and clinical-record infrastructure.
